Rioting erupted in Toledo, Ohio after counter-protestors disrupted a neo-Nazi march.
White supremacists clashed with an angry crowd outside Faneuil Hall, while Holocaust survivors commemorated the liberation of Nazi concentration camps.
A city council candidate withdrew after ties to white supremacist groups were revealed.
Mayor Jack Ford faced backlash for allowing the march, leading to violence and a state of emergency declaration.
Amidst racial tensions, calls for unity and self-respect were made by community leaders.
The situation escalated, resulting in tragic deaths and heightened security measures.
Peaceful demonstrations and efforts to prevent further violence were underway in the tense atmosphere.
